resource.chars: Fauvel, now abandon your comb
And listen to me, for I am the daughter
Of the king who, without beginning,
Reigns and who lives eternally,
And whom Scripture calls
The giant of a double nature,
For, after he put everything in order,
He wanted to be born of pure earth.
He was born without the seed of a father,
Without the action of man, or a mother.
He is the giant who through force
Vanquished death in wood without thorns.
I was born of this giant.
Because of this strong father, I am called "strong" (forte);
I am "Fortune", both "one" (une) and "strong" (forte),
But I behave differently,
And my way of being is double.
For some I am beautiful, for others a source of trouble.
I am the daughter of the king of kings,
Who entrusted to me the world and all of its troubles,
Such that I direct
Everything, as it pleased my father,
For my father, I dare to say it,
Does not do anything without reason.
Listen, Fauvel, you crazy animal:
I have a sister, a little older,
Who is called Wisdom.
She bears the banner
On which virtues are written.
All great and small things
That existed, exist or will exist
Appear clearly on the banner,
And not just their appearance,
But the entirety of their essence,
Each one in its own image,
Very clearly illuminated.
Whoever contemplates himself in this banner
Can see and read everything.
Through wisdom he created the world,
The king in whom all good resides.
Then he took the measure
Of the world and of its nature,
With wisdom he examined everything
That he had made and begun.
Wisdom is my full sister.
She made the world and I manage it,
Through the orders of my father.
I make the circle of the world and the sphere
Turn without respite.
I make night and day arrive.
All things related to movement
Are under my control.
You will be wise if you understand me.
Power is mine until the time
When all movements will cease.
Through me they begin and end,
And time is nothing but the measure
Of the movements of Nature.
Thus you can see how my father
Wanted to put me in charge
Of all things that move,
So that I find myself as their mistress.
And for this reason is the world,
Which always turns, in my power.
I possess time, through which I measure,
The speed of the world.
Never does it go so fast or slow
That I do not draw a point
Through which I control
The present as well as the past,
Even though the present is so small
That it cannot be held back.
But the aforementioned task
Will stop when motion stops,
For the world will end
As soon as movement ends.
But as long as the world endures,
It is necessary that I assume the responsibility
Of governing and leading it.
This is why I can assist or harm,
According to the turn I make,
In distributing joy and misery.
And because I change in this way,
I often throw pride down to the ground,
And I give hope to the poor,
And great comfort in their sort.
In order to better summarize my subject,
Now I would like to name myself.
Listen, animal in whom all evil resides.
Fortune is nothing other than
Divine providence,
Which orders, measures and delimits
Through the rule of good reason,
The world and its course.
Listen, you animal of ill repute!
I have at least a four-fold name.
My true name is Providence,
Which is given to me because
I have the power to see far in advance
Everything as it must occur.
I have always predicted
My turn before it was initiated.
Without neglect or lack of knowledge,
Everything depends on my foresight.
My second name is Destiny,
Which is sometimes called Fate,
Which means, literally,
Sent into movement.
In as much as I apply myself
To moving my true wheel,
And am serving this purpose,
I merit the name Destiny,
For I am the sovereign delegate,
And for this reason I also have the name Fate,
For through me is said and spoken
The secret ordinance of God.
My third name is Random Occurrence,
Which often comes, painful and hard,
Through the course of events that are not known
Until the moment when they have occurred.
My fourth name is Fortune,
For I am strong and I know how to quarrel,
And I knock down inside my walls
The rich, poor, wise and dumb.
Through what has been said, we teach you
How Fortune has four names,
Like a young maiden
Who threw from a high tower
Many stones mixed with apples
On several women and men
And knew
How what was thrown would fall.
And, since she knew how it would fall,
She would have the name Providence.
And in as much as she threw the objects,
Her name would be Destiny
And when people were injured
From the stones that fell on them,
And the others on whom the apples fell
Would not be injured,
